defaultFunding
defaultChannel 4 believes that the licence fee remains the most appropriate means of funding the BBC, but licence fee payers are right to demand excellence and value for money from the BBC. 
defaultUK PSB’s
default utilise a wide variety of funding models; from 
defaultpublic
defaultly or 
defaultpriv
defaultately o
defaultwned and commercially funded 
defaultto the BBC’s model 
defaultof publicly owned and public
defaultly funded. This diversity in models has been an important feature of the success of the UK’s PSB ecology. It encourages competition between PSBs while also allowing four to 
defaultexist, offering a range and variety of high quality content and services to suit the tastes of all audiences.   
defaultWere the BBC to shift to a commercially funded model it would be likely to negatively impact other commercially funded PSBs, and in doing so ha
defaultrm the investment in content that is central to the success of the PSB ecology in the UK.
default 
defaultAs previously mentioned in many cases the BBC is best placed to deliver maximum value for money for the licence fee payer but in many cases partnering with other org
defaultanisations would be beneficial. Channel 4 believes that
default were the BBC to 
defaultengage in considered partnership on areas where others have better expertise it 
defaultcould deliver an 
defaulteffective means of maximising the value of the licence fee. 
defaultGovernance:
defaultChannel 4 beli
defaulteves that a 10 year Royal Charter remains the most appropriate constitutional framework for the BBC. The certainty 
defaultthat 
defaulta 10 year charter provides
default,
default enables the BBC to take a long term, strategic approach to its investments which is unlikely to be possible 
defaultwith a shorter charter agreement. 
defaultHowever in a rapidly changing communications environment it would be appropriate to be able to make targeted changes to the Charter if and when appropriate.
defaultThe BBC’s current governance and regulation has come under incre
defaultased scrutiny in recent months and Channel 4 believes it is appropriate to closely examine whether the existing structure and mechanisms are still appropriate. The Trust is currently charged with being both cheerleader and regulator for the BBC and 
defaultthese d
defaultuel responsibilities often conflict with one another 
defaultso
default it is right that this is examined as part of the charter review.
defaultChannel 4 
defaultdoes not currently hold a firm view on the most appropriate governance and regulation mechanisms for the BBC but plans to eng
defaultage fully with the charter review when this process formally begins.
